# BLOG 2  \
## Why Missing Even One Vaccine Can Shorten Your Pet\'92s Life\
\
### Introduction  \
\
Most pet parents don\'92t skip vaccines intentionally.  \
They:\
\
- Forget  \
- Delay  \
- Assume one dose is enough  \
\
But science shows that even small gaps in vaccination schedules can increase risk.\
\
---\
\
### Disease Risk Without Vaccination\
\
Unvaccinated pets are significantly more vulnerable to infectious diseases.\
\
According to the American Veterinary Medical Association (AVMA):\
\
> \'93Unvaccinated pets are at significantly higher risk of contracting and spreading infectious diseases.\'94\
\
**Source:**  \
AVMA Vaccination Guidelines  \
https://www.avma.org/resources-tools/pet-owners/petcare/vaccinations\
\
---\
\
### Mortality Evidence\
\
Clinical research shows clear differences in survival rates.\
\
A study on canine parvovirus found:\
- Unvaccinated puppies had significantly higher mortality  \
- Vaccinated dogs had much better survival outcomes  \
\
**Source:**  \
Decaro et al., 2005  \
Canine parvovirus epidemiology  \
Veterinary Microbiology  \
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.vetmic.2005.03.018\
\
For cats:\
\
- Feline panleukopenia outbreaks show high fatality in unvaccinated kittens  \
\
**Source:**  \
Greene, Infectious Diseases of the Dog and Cat (4th Edition)\
\
---\
\
### The Timing Problem\
\
Vaccination effectiveness depends on correct timing.\
\
According to the American Animal Hospital Association (AAHA):\
\
> \'93Incomplete vaccination protocols may leave animals unprotected.\'94\
\
**Source:**  \
AAHA Canine Vaccination Guidelines  \
https://www.aaha.org/aaha-guidelines/vaccination-canine-configuration/\
\
---\
\
### The Hidden Risk\
\
Missing even one vaccine can:\
\
- Interrupt immunity development  \
- Create vulnerability windows  \
- Increase infection risk  \
\
This directly increases the probability of severe illness or early death.\
\
---\
\
### Final Takeaway\
\
Vaccination is not a one-time event.  \
It is a **time-sensitive process**.\
\
Missing steps can reduce protection \'97 and cost years of life.\
\
